title.narrative: HEALTH & NUTRITION POLICY AND LEGISLATION

description.narrative: National capacities enhanced to strengthen quality health and nutrition policy and legislation, particularly in target countries., which contributes to Child Health, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Maternal And Newborn Health, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Caregivers have improved knowledge and skills to adopt recommended health and nutrition care practices, particularly in target countries.

title.narrative: National capacities enhanced to strengthen quality health and nutrition policy and legislation, particularly in target countries.

description.narrative: UNICEF’s commitments coincided with national budget cycles in the Cook Islands, Fiji, Kiribati, Nauru, Niue, Solomon Islands, Tonga, Tuvalu, and Vanuatu and were articulated in the budget books of the Cook Islands, Fiji, Kiribati, Solomon Islands, Tonga, and Vanuatu. The Federated States of Micronesia (FSM), Solomon Islands, and Vanuatu made progress operationalizing their multi-sectoral nutrition coordination mechanisms. UNICEF and Solomon Islands’ Ministry of Health and Medical Services (MHMS) finalized the analysis of a service provision assessment (SPA) survey comprised of observations and client exit interviews. The results provide crucial data on primary health care (PHC) service quality, validating UNICEF’s investments. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:02/02/2022
